04829nam a22006855i 9781501753633DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212023nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017536337 a10.1515/97815017536332doi  a(DE-B1597)566273  a(OCoLC)1154891497  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD1333.C17bB4 2021 7aHIS0480002bisacsh04a333.3/15962231 aBeban, Alice, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnwritten Rule :bState-Making through Land Reform in Cambodia /cAlice Beban. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2021] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (258 p.) :b9 b&w halftones, 3 maps, 3 graphs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Series on Land: New Perspectives on Territory, Development, and Environment00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1 DONOR-STATE PARTNERSHIPS IN THE CAMBODIAN LAND SECTOR -- t2 ENCOUNTERING THE LEOPARD SKIN LAND REFORM -- t3 RECONFIGURING LOCAL AUTHORITY THROUGH LAND REFORM -- t4 YOUTH VOLUNTEERS TO THE FRONTIER -- t5 LIFE IN THE LEOPARD SKIN -- t6 COMMUNAL LAND STRUGGLES IN THE WAKE OF THE LAND REFORM -- t7 AN ONTOLOGY OF LAND BEYOND STATE-CAPITAL FORMATIONS -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2012, Cambodia—an epicenter of violent land grabbing—announced a bold new initiative to develop land redistribution efforts inside agribusiness concessions. Alice Beban's Unwritten Rule focuses on this land reform to understand the larger nature of democracy in Cambodia. Beban contends that the national land-titling program, the so-called leopard skin land reform, was first and foremost a political campaign orchestrated by the world's longest-serving prime minister, Hun Sen. The reform aimed to secure the loyalty of rural voters, produce "modern" farmers, and wrest control over land distribution from local officials. Through ambiguous legal directives and unwritten rules guiding the allocation of land, the government fostered uncertainty and fear within local communities. Unwritten Rule gives pause both to celebratory claims that land reform will enable land tenure security, and to critical claims that land reform will enmesh rural people more tightly in state bureaucracies and create a fiscally legible landscape. Instead, Beban argues that the extension of formal property rights strengthened the very patronage-based politics that Western development agencies hope to subvert.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLand reformzCambodia. 0aLand tenurexPolitical aspectszCambodia. 0aNation-buildingzCambodia. 0aPower (Social sciences)zCambodia. 4aAnthropology. 4aAsian Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Southeast Asia.2bisacsh  aLand titling, Cambodia and land, Land grabs, Land Conflicts, Post-conflict land reform.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073908408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501753633?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501753633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501753633/original  a978-3-11-073908-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 20